\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 34.} These discrepancies have been put to Mr Raj but I do not think that he has given any or any credible explanations therefor whether in cross-examination or re-examination.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 35.} For instance, in an attempt to explain KWH's said medical notes, Mr Raj claims to have told the attending doctor that after lifting a heavy object at Peak Road, he went to another site at Repulse Bay Road which is near Stanley in answer to the doctor's questions as to where he had the accident and where he worked; that he lifted the heavy object at 9:30 am; and that he only said around 12 to 1 pm when the doctor asked him when the pain started. I find it curious that the doctor should miss out the time and place of the accident. Further, the reference to 12 - 1 pm as the time when the pain started does not sit well with the statements (in paragraphs 19 and 24 of Mr Raj's witness statement) that Mr Raj felt a sharp pain in his back when he dropped the heavy object onto the pavement; that the pain in his back became severe after he had worked for about 15 to 20 minutes (from about 10:30 am) at Repulse Bay Road and that he could not tolerate the pain anymore and stopped working at about 11 am.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 36.} While one may accept that an incident causing back pain somehow occurred to Mr Raj on 29 August 2008 in view of KWH's said medical notes, in the absence of explanations that satisfactorily reconcile the aforesaid discrepancies in key aspects of Mr Raj's case on the accident and guided by the general unfavourable impression that I have formed of his overall credibility and reliability, I do not feel able to act on Mr Raj's evidence even on a balance of probabilities. In other words, Mr Raj has not discharged the burden of proving the accident as described by him.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 37.} In light of such conclusion, it is strictly unnecessary for me to address the bases upon which Mr Raj seeks to attribute liability to Yick Hing or the quantum of Mr Raj's claim. However, for the sake of completeness and in case this matter goes further and I am wrong in my conclusion on the accident, I shall also proceed to make findings on liability and quantum and give brief reasons therefor.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa120\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs22 \cf1 \b \i0 \strike0 \ul0 C. LIABILITY\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa120\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs22 \cf1 \b \i0 \strike0 \ul0 C1. Mr Raj\uc1\u8217\'6Ds case on liability\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 38.} Mr Raj's case on liability as pleaded in the re-amended statement of claim is convoluted and not easy to follow. Doing the best that I can, I understand Mr Raj to be saying that the accident he asserts was caused by: {\par}{\pard \fi-360 \li720 \ls33 
\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li720\ri0\fi-360\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 (1) the breach of the implied terms of Mr Raj's contract of employment on the part of Yick Shing "and/or" Sam Lee on the basis that Mr Raj was employed by Yick Hing "and/or" Sam Lee;\par}
}

{\pard \fi-360 \li720 \ls34 
\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li720\ri0\fi-360\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 (2) Yick Hing's negligence;\par}
}

{\pard \fi-360 \li720 \ls35 
\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li720\ri0\fi-360\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 (3) Yick Hing's breach of the common duty of care under the Occupiers' Liability Ordinance (Cap 314) ("OLO"); ii\par}
}

{\pard \fi-360 \li720 \ls36 
\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li720\ri0\fi-360\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 (4) Yick Hing's own breaches of statutory duty under \par}
}

{\pard \fi-360 \li720 \ls37 
\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li720\ri0\fi-360\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 (a) s 38A of the Construction Sites (Safety) Regulations (Cap 59I) ("CSSR");\par}
}

{\pard \fi-360 \li720 \ls38 
\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li720\ri0\fi-360\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 (b) s 6(1) of the Occupational Safety and Health Ordinance (Cap 509) ("OSHO");\par}
}

{\pard \fi-360 \li720 \ls39 
\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li720\ri0\fi-360\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 (c) ss 23(1), 24, 25, 27(1)(a), (b), (c) and (d), 27(2), 29(1)(a) and (b), 30(1), 30(2) and 31 of the Occupational Safety and Health Regulation (Cap 509A) ("OSHR"); and\par}
}

{\pard \fi-360 \li720 \ls40 
\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li720\ri0\fi-360\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 (4) Sam Lee's breaches of statutory duty under the said sections of the OSHR for which Yick Hing is said to be liable.\par}
}

\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 39.} Mr Raj further places reliance on the maxim of {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i \strike0 \ul0 res ipsa loquitur} . As I see it, there is no place in this case for this often indiscriminately pleaded maxim, which only applies in cases where the precise cause of the incident is unexplained or cannot be shown but it is more probable that it was the result of an act or omission of the defendant that amounted to a failure to take proper care of the plaintiff. See, e.g. 
\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 Sanfield Building Contractors Ltd v Li Kai Cheong (2003) 6 HKCFAR 207 \par}
, {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i \strike0 \ul0 per} Bokhary PJ at [3]. Here the precise cause of the accident is not unknown on Mr Raj's evidence. It is just that I do not accept such evidence.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 40.} The reliance on the OLO is also patently misconceived as the common duty of care under the OLO is limited in application to dangers due to the state of premises, as opposed to dangers arising from activities on land. See {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i \strike0 \ul0 Clerk & Lindsell on Torts} (21st Ed), §12-03. See also 
\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 Luen Hing Fat Coating & Finishing Factory Ltd v Waan Chuen Ming (2011) 14 HKCFAR 14 \par}
, {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i \strike0 \ul0 per} Bokhary PJ at [19].\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 41.} The attribution of vicariously liability for Sam Lee's breaches of statutory duty to Yick Hing can likewise be disposed of shortly. Vicarious liability for another person's wrong only arises where the other person is the defendant's employee or agent. See {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i \strike0 \ul0 Clerk & Lindsell on Torts}, {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i \strike0 \ul0 supra}, §6-59. Sam Lee was not the employee or agent, but an independent sub-sub-contractor, of Yick Hing.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 42.} On these notes, I turn to discuss the other bases upon which Mr Raj seeks to attach liability for the accident to Yick Hing. However, such discussion would obviously be confined to examining the applicability of the legal bases put forward by Mr Raj to say that Yick Hing was responsible for his safety at work. In view of my refusal to find the occurrence of the accident described by Mr Raj, I am not able to further consider whether Yick Hing had acted in breach even if I should find that it owed any obligation towards Mr Raj. For the same reason, I am precluded from addressing whether Mr Raj was contributorily negligent.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa120\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs22 \cf1 \b \i0 \strike0 \ul0 C2. Yick Hing not in breach of Mr Raj\uc1\u8217\'6Ds contract of employment - Mr Raj not employed by Yick Hing\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 43.} As noted in paragraph 38(1) above, it is suggested in the re-amended statement of claim that Mr Raj was employed by Yick Hing and/or Sam Lee. This relatively late averment by re-amendment to the amended statement of claim raises 3 different scenarios: {\par}{\pard \fi-360 \li720 \ls41 
\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li720\ri0\fi-360\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 (1) that Mr Raj was employed by Yick Hing only;\par}
}

{\pard \fi-360 \li720 \ls42 
\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li720\ri0\fi-360\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 (2) that Mr Raj was employed by Sam Lee only; or\par}
}

{\pard \fi-360 \li720 \ls43 
\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li720\ri0\fi-360\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 (3) that Mr Raj was employed by both Yick Hing and Sam Lee.\par}
}

\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 44.} Despite the confusion caused by the statement in paragraph 1 of Mr Raj's opening submissions that he was employed by Sam Lee, Mr Raj has at the beginning of the trial clarified and confirmed that he is putting forward the first-mentioned scenario.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 45.} However, despite such clarification and confirmation, it has become clear in the course of his cross-examination that he does not really know by whom he was employed at the material time, which he has expressly acknowledged in answer to my direct question.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 46.} The modern approach to the question whether a person is in business on his own or another's employee as set out by the Court of Final Appeal in 
\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 Poon CHau Nam v Yim Siu Cheung t/a Yat Cheung Air Conditioning & Electric Co (2007) 10 HKCFAR 156 \par}
, {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i \strike0 \ul0 per} Ribeiro PJ at [17]-[18] has been applied to the determination of the question whether one person is another's employee. See, for example, 
\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 Chan Wai Keung v Li Yau Hing DCEC 1232/2010 \par}
, unreported (11 April 2013), {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i \strike0 \ul0 per} District Court Judge HC Wong at [30]-[31] and 
\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 Shen Li Ping v Oriental Logistics Group Ltd DCEC 987/2010 \par}
, unreported (25 October 2012), {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i \strike0 \ul0 per} Deputy District Court Judge Clement Lee at [6]-[9].\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 47.} Following the same approach, in view of Mr Raj's concession that he does not really who his employer was at the material time, one should turn to examine all the features of the relationship between Mr Raj and Yick Hing. However, the evidence adduced by Mr Raj has left the court with very little to work with. {\par}{\pard \fi-360 \li720 \ls44 
\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li720\ri0\fi-360\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 (1) The person who first recruited Mr Raj (i.e. Mr Rai), though said to be employed by Sam Lee and/or Yick Hing in Mr Raj's witness statement, had in fact never told Mr Raj who he worked for. The highest that Mr Raj can put it is that Mr Rai had said that "we are under Yick Hing" which Mr Raj understands to mean that Yick Hing was the main contractor.\par}
}

{\pard \fi-360 \li720 \ls45 
\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li720\ri0\fi-360\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 (2) Mr Raj has claimed in cross-examination that Ah Fai and Ah Pi under whose supervision Mr Raj and his co-workers worked from 2 January to 8 March 2008 and from 3 July to 29 August 2008 were Yick Hing's employees. The only basis upon which Mr Raj says so is that he had seen them 5 to 6 times when he went to Yick Ying's depot at Victoria Road. However, Ah Fai and Ah Pi's attendance and presence at Yick Hing's said depot is neither here nor there. Mr Liu's evidence is that Yick Hing's said depot accommodated other companies such as Mott Connell Limited (the engineer for the project) and Sam Lee and that Sam Lee had container offices there. This seems to me to be in line with clause 2.3 of the sub-sub-contract between Yick Shing and Sam Lee under which Sam Lee could use the depot erected by Yick Shing. I accept Mr Liu's evidence.\par}
}

{\pard \fi-360 \li720 \ls46 
\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li720\ri0\fi-360\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 (3) There is nothing else in Mr Raj's evidence that throws light on his relationship with Yick Hing, if any.\par}
}

\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 48.} This state of evidence clearly does not provide any or any sufficient basis for a finding that Mr Raj was employed by Yick Hing. I make no such finding.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 49.} To the contrary, the following body of evidence points to Mr Raj being an employee of Sam Lee as a matter of probabilities and I so find. {\par}{\pard \fi-360 \li720 \ls47 
\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li720\ri0\fi-360\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 (1) As between Yick Hing, Yick Shing and Sam Lee, the obligation to provide labourers for the Works fell ultimately on Sam Lee. See clauses 2.2, 2.4 and 12(1) of the sub-subcontract between Yick Shing and Sam Lee.\par}
}

{\pard \fi-360 \li720 \ls48 
\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li720\ri0\fi-360\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 (2) Mr Liu has produced as appendices I, III, IV and V to his first statement various records kept in respect of Mr Raj's attendance and wages from 2 January to 7 March 2008 and from 3 July to 29 August 2008. According to Mr Liu, Yick Hing obtained these documents from Sam Lee. I have no reason to question such evidence.\par}
}

{\pard \fi-360 \li720 \ls49 
\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li720\ri0\fi-360\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 (3) Included in such documents is a copy of Sam Lee's cheque dated 31 January 2008 in favour of Mr Raj for the sum of $1,440 the receipt of which Mr Raj has confirmed as part of his wages for January 2008.\par}
}

{\pard \fi-360 \li720 \ls50 
\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li720\ri0\fi-360\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 (4) As said earlier, Mr Raj and his co-workers recovered arrears of wages for the period from 2 January to 7 March 2008 by enlisting the help of the Labour Department. In Mr Raj's notice of claim for wages due under ss 43D(1)/43H(1) of the Employment Ordinance (Cap 57) ("EO"), Sam Lee was put down as Mr Raj's employer. According to Mr Raj, this part of the form was filled in by the Labour Department after having been briefed about Mr Raj and his co-workers' situation but he does not know from where the Labour Department obtained Sam Lee's name. However, common sense would suggest that it is more probable than not that the Labour Department got the name of the workers' employer from the workers themselves. I note that Mr Raj signed the form after it had been completed because he thought that its content was correct.\par}
}

{\pard \fi-360 \li720 \ls51 
\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li720\ri0\fi-360\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 (5) Mr Raj's claim for arrears of wages ($34,160) was eventually settled for $25,120 paid by 3 cheques of Sam Lee totalling $12,000 and 2 cheques of Yick Hing totalling $13,120. Sam Lee would have had no reason to pay part of Mr Raj's outstanding wages if it had not been Mr Raj's employer whereas Yick Hing as the principal contractor above Sam Lee, was obliged under s 43C(1) of the EO to pay the wages of Mr Raj not paid by Sam Lee within time.\par}
}

{\pard \fi-360 \li720 \ls52 
\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li720\ri0\fi-360\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 (6) Mr Raj himself put down Sam Lee as his employer at the time of the accident in the questionnaire in support of his application for legal aid.\par}
}

\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 50.} Since Yick Hing was not Mr Raj's employer, it could not have been in breach of Mr Raj's contract of employment.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa120\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs22 \cf1 \b \i0 \strike0 \ul0 C3. Yick Hing not negligent - Yick Hing owed no tortious duty of care to Mr Raj\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 51.} On the question whether Yick Hing as the principal contractor owed a duty of care under the law of negligence to Mr Raj (an employee of Yick Hing's independent sub-subcontractor), Mr Leung refers me to 
\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 Ng Tat Kuen v Tam Che Fu HCPI 896/2013 \par}
, unreported (26 October 2015), in which Mr Justice To, referring to Lord Bridge's speech in 
\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 Caparo Industries Plc v Dickman [1990] 2 AC 605 \par}
ay 617H-618C and Bokhary PJ's judgment in {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i \strike0 \ul0 Luen Hing Fat Coating & Finishing Factory Ltd v Waan Chuen Ming}, {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i \strike0 \ul0 supra,} at [30], summarised at [26]-[27], {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i \strike0 \ul0 inter alia}, that whether a duty of care is owed under the law of negligence depends on foreseeability, proximity and whether it would be fair, just and reasonable to impose a duty of care.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 52.} Again, Mr Raj has given the court very little material to work with.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 53.} Save for his complaints about not being provided with proper equipment or sufficient manpower in moving the heavy object, Mr Raj has not in his evidence dealt with whether generally any, and if so what, system of work (in terms of provision of proper equipment and sufficient manpower and adoption of safe methods and procedure etc) was put in place by Sam Lee for the movement of heavy objects at the sites where the Works under its sub-subcontractor with Yick Shing were carried out. It follows that there is no evidence of any general lack of an effective or sufficient system of work for the movement of heavy objects, not to mention Yick Hing's awareness of the same. This case is therefore distinguishable from, e.g. 
\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 Gauchan Som Prasad v Hin Wah Construction Co Ltd DCPI 2398/2009 \par}
, unreported (26 July 2011) in which the principal contractor was held by District Court Judge Lok (as he then was) to owe a duty of care to the employees of his subcontractor on the basis of its knowledge of the defective system of work and control or supervision over such defective system of work.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 54.} More importantly, even on Mr Raj's version of the accident, there is no evidence that Yick Hing knew or should have known that Mr Raj would be instructed to move (unassisted) a heavy object from Sam Lee's van on the roadside to the pavement outside 28 Peak Road, which was not even within the site for slope maintenance work, on 29 August 2008.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 55.} I do not see any evidential basis to impose upon Yick Hing in favour of Mr Raj a duty of care under the law of negligence in respect of the activity alleged by Mr Raj to have caused him injury on 29 August 2008.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa120\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs22 \cf1 \b \i0 \strike0 \ul0 C4. Yick Hing not in breach of statutory duty - statutory provisions pleaded not applicable\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa120\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs22 \cf1 \b \i0 \strike0 \ul0 C4.1 CSSR\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 56.} Section 38A of the CSSR is clearly irrelevant as it deals with hazards arising from working at a height, requires safe access to and egress from a place of work and prevents access to a place on site in a hazardous condition.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa120\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs22 \cf1 \b \i0 \strike0 \ul0 C4.2 OSHO\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 57.} Section 6(1) of the OSHO imposes a duty to ensure the safety and health at work only upon the employer which is defined in s 3(1) as a person who employs natural persons under contracts of employment or apprenticeship.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 58.} Mr Raj's case against Yick Hing based on this section falls away with my finding that Yick Hing was not Mr Raj's employer.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa120\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs22 \cf1 \b \i0 \strike0 \ul0 C4.3 OSHR\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 59.} To recap, Mr Raj relies on ss 23(1), 24, 25, 27(1)(a), (b), (c) and (d), 27(2), 29(1)(a) and (b), 30(1), 30(2) and 31 of the OSHR.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 60.} The case based on ss 30 and 31 can be disposed of right away as the duties thereunder are imposed on the employer, which Yick Hing was not.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 61.} As for ss 23, 24, 25, 27 and 29, leaving aside the contents of the duties arising thereunder, they apply to "the person responsible for the workplace".\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 62.} A "workplace" means any place where employees work. See s 3(1) of the OSHO.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 63.} Section 3(2) of the OSHO defines "the person responsible for the workplace" to be "the employer of the employees who are employed to carry out work there, or if the employer does not exercise any degree of control over the relevant part or aspect of the workplace, means the occupier of the workplace". The "occupier", in relation to any premises or workplace, is defined by s 3(1) to include "a person who has any degree of control over the premises or workplace" and, in particular, a person to whom s 3(5) and (6) applies (which has no application in the present case).\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 64.} As explained by Mr Justice To in {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i \strike0 \ul0 Ng Tat Kuen v Tam Che Fu}, {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i \strike0 \ul0 supra}, at [53]-[55], the duties of "the person responsible for the workplace" under the OSHO and OSHR are imposed primarily upon the employer of the employees employed at the workplace. It is only if the employer does not exercise any degree of control over the workplace or the relevant part of the workplace that the responsibility is passed to the occupier. Though an inclusive definition of "occupier" is given, the essence in the occupier of the workplace must be his power to exercise control, in addition to the fact of his occupation of the workplace.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 65.} I have already found Sam Lee, and not Yick Hing, to be Mr Raj's employer. Hence, ss 23, 24, 25, 27 and 29 of the OSHR would bind Yick Hing only if Sam Lee did not exercise any degree of control, while Yick Hing had some degree of control, over the relevant workplace.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 66.} The relevant workplace for present purpose must be the roadside and pavement outside 28 Peak Road, which was not the site for slope maintenance work. That area was a public place to which all members of the public could have access. No one was in exclusive occupation. Indeed, Yick Hing had no presence or power whatsoever there. I do not see how Yick Hing can be said to have any degree of control over such a place. See again {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i \strike0 \ul0 Ng Tat Kuen v Tam Che Fu} at [62]-[66].\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 67.} To conclude, Mr Raj would have no case against Yick Hing under the OSHR (even on his version of the accident).\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa120\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs22 \cf1 \b \i0 \strike0 \ul0 D. QUANTUM\par}

