\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 90.} Mr Raj takes issue with these Sam Lee records disclosed by Yick Hing, saying that he played no part in their compilation and that he remembers doing 1 to 2 hours of overtime work everyday. I do not accept such challenge. Quite apart from the facts that it is unsupported by any evidence other than Mr Raj's bare assertion and that I have come to a negative view on Mr Raj's credibility and reliability, Mr Raj is demonstrably wrong on one point about the record kepts by Sam Lee in respect of his attendance. Mr Raj insists that he worked on 6 January 2008, in the course of which he sustained an injury to his left ring finger. According to Sam Lee's records, 6 January 2008 was a day off. It was in fact a Sunday which is usually a day off. In fact, Mr Raj went to Queen Elizabeth Hospital to seek medical treatment for his finger injury on 6 January 2008. According to the relevant medical notes, Mr Raj told the attending doctor that he was injured "yesterday", i.e. on 5 January 2008.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 91.} I find that Mr Raj worked about 20 days per month at a daily wage of $430 thereby earning $8,600 per month at time of injury on 29 August 2008.\par}

